ill help you write a better plan.\n- Always start new conversation by loading `/using-superpowers` skill. Do this automatically without being asked.\n  - Ignore `superpowers:using-git-worktrees` skill.\n- Do **not** launch Bash / console commands in the background using `command &` syntax, you have options to run Bash and other tools in background explicitly.\n\n## External File Loading\n\nCRITICAL: When you encounter a file reference (e.g., @rules/general.md), use your Read tool to load it on a need-to-know basis. They're relevant to the SPECIFIC task at hand.\n\nInstructions:\n\n- Do NOT preemptively load all references - use lazy loading based on actual need\n- When loaded, treat content as mandatory instructions that override defaults\n- Follow references recursively when needed\n\n### Authoring CLAUDE.md / AGENTS.md\n\n`@file` references in CLAUDE.md / AGENTS.md are eagerly injected into agent context on every load by the Claude Code loader, regardless of whether the file is needed for the current task. The lazy-load instructions above govern in-conversation Read behavior; they do NOT override loader-level injection. Authoring choices matter:\n\n- Use `@file` ONLY for small, always-relevant docs (rule of thumb: ≤ ~50 lines and you'd want the content in every conversation in that directory).\n- Use plain markdown links `[file](file)` for everything larger or situational — agents will Read on demand.\n- Authoring heuristic: if you would not paste the file's full contents into every conversation that triggers this CLAUDE.md, do not use `@`.\n- This applies to both `CLAUDE.md` and `AGENTS.md` (and `.claude.local.md`), and to symlinks between them.\n\n--- project-doc ---\n\n# Agent instructions — llame\n\nHow to work in this repo. [SPEC.md](SPEC.md) is the current cross-cutting architecture contract and documentation index; focused capability behavior lives in OpenSpec. `CLAUDE.md` and `GEMINI.md` are symlinks to this file.\n\nThe product overview (what llame is) is